definition: "A complete blood count (CBC) is a panel of tests that measures the cellular components of blood: red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. Key CBC metrics include hemoglobin (the oxygen-carrying protein in red blood cells), hematocrit (the percentage of blood volume occupied by red blood cells), mean corpuscular volume (MCV, the average red blood cell size), white blood cell count and differential (the breakdown of WBC types), and platelet count. The CBC is the most frequently ordered blood test in medicine and provides a window into nutritional status, immune function, bone marrow activity, and systemic inflammatory state."
why_it_matters: "From a longevity perspective, the CBC contains several markers that independently predict mortality and biological aging in population studies — and that are routinely under-interpreted in standard clinical practice. White blood cell count, even within the normal range, shows a dose-response relationship with all-cause mortality. The neutrophil-to-lymphocyte ratio (NLR) — derived from the WBC differential — is a powerful marker of chronic systemic inflammation and immune aging. Red blood cell distribution width (RDW) — a measure of variation in red blood cell size — predicts all-cause mortality more powerfully than many conventional risk markers. Hemoglobin and hematocrit reveal nutritional adequacy and anemia risk. Together, these CBC-derived markers paint a picture of physiological resilience that extends well beyond the simple 'normal vs. abnormal' read that most standard panels provide."

